=> Microservices Inter-Communication Complete Flow

    -> Microservices need to communicate with each other to exchange data and perform business operations.

    -> There are mainly 2 communication types:
          1. Synchronous Communication
          2. Asynchronous Communication

================================================================================

=> 1. Synchronous Communication

    -> Definition
          -> Service A sends request to Service B.
          -> Service A waits until Service B returns response.
          -> Communication is Blocking in nature.

    -> Flow

          Client
             |
             v
         Service A
             |
             | Request
             v
         Service B
             |
             | Response
             v
         Service A

    -> Characteristics
          -> Request-Response model.
          -> Blocking communication.
          -> Caller waits for response.
          -> Suitable when immediate response is required.

    -> Common Tools
          -> RestTemplate (Blocking by default)
          -> WebClient + block() method

    -> RestTemplate Example
          -> Always synchronous.
          -> Current thread waits for response.

    -> WebClient Example
          -> By default Non-Blocking.
          -> If block() is used, it becomes Synchronous.

    -> Example

          User requests Account Summary

          Service A (Account Service)
                 |
                 v
          Service B (Transaction Service)

          Service A waits for transaction details then returns final response.

    -> Disadvantage

          -> Tight Coupling

          Service A -------> Service B

          If Service B is down Service A may fail or become slow.

================================================================================

=> 2. Asynchronous Communication

    -> Definition
          -> Service A sends request/event.
          -> Does NOT wait for response.
          -> Processing happens independently.

    -> Communication Types

          1. One-to-One
          2. One-to-Many

================================================================================

=> 2.1 Asynchronous One-to-One Communication

    -> Flow

          Service A
               |
               | Async Request
               v
          Service B

    -> Characteristics

          -> Direct communication.
          -> No blocking.
          -> Service A continues execution.
          -> Response can be processed later.

    -> Tool

          -> WebClient

    -> Why WebClient?

          -> Non-blocking.
          -> Reactive.
          -> Better resource utilization.
          -> Suitable for high concurrent requests.

    -> Example

          User uploads document.

          Service A sends async request to Document Processing Service.

          Service A continues processing without waiting.

================================================================================

=> 2.2 Asynchronous One-to-Many Communication

    -> Requirement

          -> One event should be consumed by multiple services.

    -> Solution

          -> Event-Driven Architecture

================================================================================

=> Event-Driven Architecture

    -> Definition

          -> Producer publishes event.
          -> Multiple consumers receive event.
          -> Services remain independent.

    -> Flow

                         Kafka Topic
                              |
                ------------------------------
                |             |             |
                v             v             v
           Service B     Service C     Service D

          Producer Service A
                   |
                   v
             Publish Event

    -> Real Example

          Order Created Event

          Service A (Order Service)
                     |
                     v
                Kafka Topic
                     |
           ----------------------
           |         |          |
           v         v          v

      Billing    Shipping   Notification
      Service    Service     Service

    -> Benefits

          -> Loose Coupling
          -> High Scalability
          -> Better Fault Tolerance
          -> Independent Deployment
          -> Better Performance

    -> Advantage over WebClient

          WebClient

          Service A -------> Service B

          If Service B is down Request may fail.

          Event-Driven

          Service A --> Kafka --> Service B

          If Service B is down Kafka stores messages. Service B can consume later.

================================================================================

=> Event-Driven Tools

    -> Apache Kafka
    -> RabbitMQ
    -> Amazon SQS
    -> ActiveMQ

================================================================================

=> Reactive Programming

    -> Definition

          -> Programming model designed to handle large number of concurrent requests efficiently.

          -> Uses Non-Blocking I/O.

          -> Threads are not wasted waiting for database/API response.

================================================================================

=> Spring Reactive Stack

    -> Spring WebFlux

          -> Reactive Web Framework.

    -> Project Reactor

          -> Reactive Library used by WebFlux.

          -> Provides:
                -> Mono
                -> Flux

================================================================================

=> Mono

    -> Represents 0 or 1 result.

    -> Used when only one object is expected.

    -> Examples

          Get User By Id
          Get Order By Id
          Get Account Summary

    -> Flow

          Request
             |
             v
         Mono<User>

    -> Returns Single Object

================================================================================

=> Flux

    -> Represents 0 to N results.

    -> Used when multiple records are expected.

    -> Examples

          Get All Users
          Get All Employees
          Stream Stock Prices
          Chat Messages

    -> Flow

          Request
             |
             v
      Flux<User>

          User1
          User2
          User3
          User4
          ....

================================================================================

=> Mono vs Flux

    -> Mono

          -> Single Result
          -> 0 or 1 element
          -> Example:
                Get User By Id

    -> Flux

          -> Multiple Results
          -> 0 to N elements
          -> Example:
                Get All Users From Bangalore

================================================================================

=> Why Flux Instead of Mono<List<User>> ?

    -> Mono<List<User>>

          Database
               |
               v
      Collect all 10,000 users
               |
               v
      Return complete list

          -> User waits for entire result.

    -> Flux<User>

          Database
               |
               v

          User1 ---->
          User2 ---->
          User3 ---->
          User4 ---->

          -> Data starts flowing immediately.
          -> Better memory utilization.
          -> True Reactive Streaming.

================================================================================

=> Complete Decision Flow

    -> Need immediate response?
          -> YES
                -> Synchronous
                -> RestTemplate
                -> WebClient + block()

    -> Need asynchronous communication?
          -> YES

                -> One-to-One?
                      -> WebClient

                -> One-to-Many?
                      -> Event-Driven Architecture
                      -> Kafka / RabbitMQ

    -> Need high scalability and non-blocking processing?
          -> Use Spring WebFlux

                -> Single Result?
                      -> Mono

                -> Multiple Results?
                      -> Flux

================================================================================

=> Final Interview Summary

    -> Synchronous = Blocking = RestTemplate / WebClient.block()

    -> Asynchronous One-to-One = WebClient

    -> Asynchronous One-to-Many = Event-Driven Architecture

    -> Kafka/RabbitMQ enable Publisher-Subscriber model

    -> Reactive Programming = Non-Blocking + High Scalability

    -> Spring WebFlux uses Project Reactor

    -> Mono = Single Result

    -> Flux = Stream of Multiple Results

======================================================Reactive Programming Internal Flow=======================================================

    -> Reactive Programming Internal Flow

          -> Traditional Spring MVC follows Thread Per Request Model.

          -> One request gets one dedicated thread.

          -> Same thread handles:
                -> Receiving request.
                -> Business processing.
                -> Database/API call.
                -> Waiting for response.
                -> Returning response.

          -> Flow:

                Request-1
                    |
                    v
                Thread-1
                    |
                    v
                Call Database
                    |
                    v
                Wait For Result
                    |
                    v
                Return Response

          -> Problem:
                -> Thread remains blocked while waiting.
                -> CPU does no useful work during waiting period.
                -> Large number of requests require large number of threads.
                -> High memory consumption.

================================================================================

    -> How WebFlux Solves This Problem

          -> WebFlux follows Event Loop Model.

          -> When request arrives:
                -> Event Loop Thread receives request.
                -> Reactive pipeline (Mono/Flux) is created.
                -> Database/API call is initiated.
                -> Thread is immediately released.

          -> Flow:

                Request-1
                    |
                    v
                EventLoop-1
                    |
                    v
                Database/API Call
                    |
                    v
                Save Pipeline State In Mono/Flux
                    |
                    v
                Release EventLoop-1

          -> EventLoop-1 is now free to process:
                -> Request-2
                -> Request-3
                -> Request-4
                -> Request-5

================================================================================

    -> What Happens To The Waiting Request?

          -> Request is NOT lost.

          -> Mono/Flux remembers:
                -> Pending operation.
                -> Remaining execution steps.
                -> Connection information.
                -> Response callback chain.

          -> Framework stores the pipeline state.

          -> Request is waiting for data, not for a thread.

================================================================================

    -> When Database/API Returns Result

          -> Database completes operation.
          -> Operating System sends notification.
          -> Netty Event Loop receives notification.
          -> Any available Event Loop Thread continues processing.

          -> Flow:

                Database Result Ready
                       |
                       v
                EventLoop-2(any available thread) Picks Event
                       |
                       v
                Resume Mono/Flux Pipeline
                       |
                       v
                Process Result
                       |
                       v
                Return Response To User

================================================================================

    -> Does Same Thread Return The Response?

          -> Not necessarily.

          -> Request may start on EventLoop-1.
          -> Response may be returned by EventLoop-2.
          -> Response may be returned by EventLoop-3.

          -> WebFlux tracks pipeline state, not thread state.

          -> Example:

                Request Received By EventLoop-1
                            |
                            v
                     External API Call
                            |
                            v
                     EventLoop-1 Released

                API Response Arrives
                            |
                            v
                     EventLoop-3 Processes Result
                            |
                            v
                     Response Returned To User

================================================================================

    -> Spring MVC vs WebFlux Thread Handling

          -> Spring MVC

                One Request
                      |
                      v
                One Dedicated Thread
                      |
                      v
                Same Thread Finishes Everything

          -> WebFlux

                One Request
                      |
                      v
                Reactive Pipeline Created
                      |
                      v
                Thread Released During Waiting
                      |
                      v
                Any Available Thread Can Continue Processing
                      |
                      v
                Response Returned

================================================================================

    -> Why WebFlux Scales Better

          -> Threads are not blocked.
          -> Small thread pool can handle many requests.
          -> Better CPU utilization.
          -> Lower memory consumption.
          -> High concurrency support.
          -> Suitable for I/O intensive systems.